The snapshot has no indexed files, so I'll reason entirely from the described stack and the symptoms. Here is the full diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

Two distinct but related problems, both rooted in the same source:

| # | Symptom | Count |
|---|---------|-------|
| 1 | Inline `**bold**` spans used as scan anchors instead of structural headings | 36 across 7 body blocks |
| 2 | No visible breathing room / hierarchy between sections because those anchors are the *only* visual landmarks | — |

The user supplied Markdown that cargo-culted a "document scan" convention (`**Per user.**`, `**Scaffolding.**`, `**Conclusion.**`) where each bolded label pretends to be a heading but is rendered inside a `<p>` tag. The RichText serialiser faithfully wraps every `**…**` in `<strong>`, so the rendered page has 36 typographic shouts with no corresponding structure. This violates **AP-072 (Semantic-weight inflation)** — bold is reserved for genuine stress emphasis, not structural navigation — and **EAP-027 (Label-as-heading anti-pattern)** — using inline weight to fake document structure instead of promoting the node to an actual heading level.

---

## Root Cause

### AP-072 — Semantic-weight inflation
`<strong>` / `font-bold` is drained of meaning when used more than ~2–3 times per screen. 36 instances across 7 bodies means *everything* is emphatic, so nothing is.

### EAP-027 — Label-as-heading anti-pattern
The source Markdown author used bold as a pseudo-heading (`**Scaffolding.**`) instead of `### Scaffolding`. These nodes should be promoted to real `<h3>` / `<h4>` elements so the serialiser can attach spacing tokens and typographic scale, not raw weight.

---

## Fix

The fix has **three layers**: (1) sanitise the source content, (2) harden the serialiser so this can never silently re-enter, (3) add the section-break styling that was missing even for real headings.

---

### Layer 1 — Content: promote pseudo-heading bold spans to real headings

In your Payload CMS rich-text field (Lexical or Slate depending on your version), each body block's JSON nodes should be edited so that any top-level paragraph whose *only* child is a bold text node becomes an `h3` heading node instead.

**Before (Lexical JSON, one body block excerpt):**
```json
{
  "type": "paragraph",
  "children": [
    { "text": "Scaffolding.", "bold": true }
  ]
}
```

**After:**
```json
{
  "type": "heading",
  "tag": "h3",
  "children": [
    { "text": "Scaffolding." }
  ]
}
```

Repeat for every one of the ~36 nodes that follow this pattern (`Per user.`, `Scaffolding.`, `Conclusion.`, etc.). Bold is removed from the child; the heading tag carries the weight semantically.

If you are importing via a migration script, add this transform:

```ts
// src/migrations/promoteBoldParagraphsToHeadings.ts
import type { SerializedLexicalNode } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'

/** Promotes a paragraph whose sole child is a bold text node into an h3. */
export function promoteBoldAnchors(
  nodes: SerializedLexicalNode[],
): SerializedLexicalNode[] {
  return nodes.map((node) => {
    // Recurse into children first
    if ('children' in node && Array.isArray(node.children)) {
      node = { ...node, children: promoteBoldAnchors(node.children) }
    }

    if (
      node.type === 'paragraph' &&
      'children' in node &&
      Array.isArray(node.children) &&
      node.children.length === 1 &&
      node.children[0].type === 'text' &&
      (node.children[0] as any).bold === true
    ) {
      return {
        ...node,
        type: 'heading',
        tag: 'h3',
        children: [{ ...node.children[0], bold: false }],
      }
    }

    return node
  })
}
```

Run this transform once against every stored `body` field value in the database before deploying the render-layer changes below.

---

### Layer 2 — Serialiser: add a guard against future bold-only paragraphs

```ts
// src/components/RichText/serialize.tsx  (simplified Lexical serialiser)
import type { SerializedLexicalNode, SerializedTextNode } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'

function isBoldOnlyParagraph(node: SerializedLexicalNode): boolean {
  if (node.type !== 'paragraph') return false
  const children = (node as any).children ?? []
  return (
    children.length === 1 &&
    children[0].type === 'text' &&
    children[0].bold === true
  )
}

export function serialize(nodes: SerializedLexicalNode[]): React.ReactNode {
  return nodes.map((node, i) => {
    // --- Guard: promote any bold-only paragraph that slipped through ---
    if (isBoldOnlyParagraph(node)) {
      const text = ((node as any).children[0] as SerializedTextNode).text
      return (
        <h3 key={i} className="essay-section-heading">
          {text}
        </h3>
      )
    }

    // ... rest of your existing switch/if chain
  })
}
```

This makes the serialiser self-healing: even if an editor re-introduces the pattern, it renders as a proper heading rather than a fat `<p>`.

---

### Layer 3 — Styles: section heading tokens + body breathing room

Add these utility classes to your Tailwind / Elan design-token layer. The key moves are:
- `essay-section-heading` gets **size + spacing**, not extra bold weight (the heading element itself is already bold by browser default; we reset it to `font-medium` to avoid the double-weight shout).
- A visible top rule (`border-t`) creates the section separation that was previously faked by bold labels.

```css
/* src/styles/essay.css  (imported in your global stylesheet) */

@layer components {
  /* ── Section heading promoted from bold-only paragraph ─────────────── */
  .essay-section-heading {
    /* Scale: one step above body, below article title */
    font-size: var(--text-lg);          /* e.g. 1.125 rem */
    font-weight: var(--font-medium);    /* 500 — not heavy, the rule does the work */
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
    color: var(--color-fg-primary);

    /* Section break */
    margin-block-start: var(--space-10); /* 2.5 rem — generous gap above */
    padding-block-start: var(--space-6); /* 1.5 rem — space between rule and text */
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);

    margin-block-end: var(--space-3);   /* tight to the paragraph that follows */
  }

  /* ── Body prose: restore <strong> to rare genuine emphasis only ─────── */
  .essay-body strong {
    font-weight: var(--font-semibold);  /* 600, unchanged */
    /* No color change — weight alone is the signal */
  }

  /* Guard: if somehow a bold-only paragraph still renders as <p>,
     make it visually obvious in dev so it gets caught. */
  @layer utilities {
    .essay-body p:has(> strong:only-child) {
      outline: 2px dashed var(--color-warning-400);  /* dev-only, see below */
    }
  }
}
```

Add a `dev-only` conditional around the `p:has(> strong:only-child)` outline so it never ships to production:

```tsx
// src/components/EssayBody/EssayBody.tsx
export function EssayBody({ content }: { content: SerializedLexicalNode[] }) {
  return (
    <article
      className={[
        'essay-body',
        process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development' ? 'essay-body--debug' : '',
      ]
        .filter(Boolean)
        .join(' ')}
    >
      <RichText nodes={content} />
    </article>
  )
}
```

```css
/* Only applies in dev builds */
.essay-body--debug p:has(> strong:only-child) {
  outline: 2px dashed var(--color-warning-400);
}
```

---

## Before / After

| Before | After |
|--------|-------|
| 36 `<strong>` spans, visually noisy, semantically meaningless | 0 bold scan-anchor spans; each promoted to `<h3>` |
| No visual section breaks — sections blur together | `border-top` + `margin-block-start: 2.5rem` creates clean breathing room |
| Section "headings" render at paragraph size | `--text-lg` + `--tracking-wide` elevates them one clear step above body |
| `<strong>` appears ~5× per screen | `<strong>` reserved for genuine stress emphasis (~0–2 per body) |
| No dev guard against recurrence | Serialiser self-heals + dev outline catches regressions |

---

## Principle

> **Bold is stress, not structure. Structure needs elements.**

`<strong>` communicates *this word matters more than its neighbours*. It borrows its meaning from the surrounding text. A heading communicates *a new section begins here* — that is a document-outline concern, not a typographic one. When an author uses bold to fake a heading, they get the visual weight without the semantic node, which means: no spacing tokens fire, no `<h3>` lands in the accessibility tree, no table-of-contents can be generated, and — most visibly — the reader gets 36 shouts instead of 6 quiet signposts. Promote the node; let the element do its job.
